	abstract = {We present the first cosmological study of a sample of \$eROSITA\$ clusters, which were identified in the \$eROSITA\$ Final Equatorial Depth Survey (eFEDS). In a joint selection on X-ray and optical observables, the sample contains \$455\$ clusters within a redshift range of \$0.1{\textless}z{\textless}1.2\$, of which \$177\$ systems are covered by the public data from the Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC) survey that enables uniform weak-lensing cluster mass constraints. With minimal assumptions, at each cluster redshift \$z\$ we empirically model (1) the scaling relations between the cluster halo mass \$M\$ and the observables, which include the X-ray count rate \${\textbackslash}eta\$, the optical richness \${\textbackslash}lambda\$, and the weak-lensing mass \$M\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{WL\}\}\$, and (2) the X-ray selection in terms of the completeness function \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{C\}\$. Using the richness distribution of the clusters, we directly measure the X-ray completeness and adopt those measurements as informative priors for the parameters of \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{C\}\$. We validate our cosmology analysis framework using mock data, and then in a blinded analysis of the real data we further validate the joint modeling of the cluster abundance and the weak-lensing mass calibration with a set of consistency tests. After unblinding, we obtain the cosmological constraints \${\textbackslash}Omega\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{m\}\} = 0.245{\textasciicircum}\{+0.048\}\_\{-0.058\}\$, \${\textbackslash}sigma\_\{8\} = 0.833{\textasciicircum}\{+0.075\}\_\{-0.063\}\$ and \$S\_\{8\} {\textbackslash}equiv {\textbackslash}sigma\_\{8\}{\textbackslash}left({\textbackslash}Omega\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{m\}\}/0.3{\textbackslash}right){\textasciicircum}\{0.3\}= 0.791{\textasciicircum}\{+0.028\}\_\{-0.031\}\$ in a flat \${\textbackslash}Lambda\$CDM cosmology. Extending to a flat \$w\$CDM cosmology leads to the constraint on the equation of state parameter of the dark energy of \$w = -1.25{\textbackslash}pm 0.47\$. The eFEDS constraints are in good agreement with the results from the \$Planck\$ mission, the galaxy-galaxy lensing and clustering analysis of the Dark Energy Survey, and the cluster abundance analysis of the SPT-SZ survey at a level of \${\textbackslash}lesssim1{\textbackslash}sigma\$. (abridged)},
